What you describe above is right on the mark.

In a world where &quot;down&quot; is almost always just &quot;mostly dead&quot; instead of
&quot;all dead&quot; it's often more valuable to finish off a particularly dangerous
threat than to move on to the next still-standing opponent.  After all, it
only takes one meddlesome cleric or paladin to lay on hands and that
&quot;mostly dead&quot; opponent is back in the fight and is again a serious threat.
And it also only takes one attack to lop off the head of a fallen and
helpless opponent.

This was made *extremely* clear to me in a battle where I had pitted the
entire party against a single tough big boss in some tight spaces
undergroud.

Some background:

I have a few old friends that like to play bad guys but who don't have the
time to play DnD regularly.  So for a lot of the major confrontations
between the player party and my major bad guys, I'll invite in one of
these old friends to play &quot;a special guest villan&quot;.

It frees me up a lot to concern myself with all the flunkys and managing
the environment.  And it makes the actual encounter a lot more focused...
with a dedicated and undistracted master villan to deal with.

So my players have this Hobgoblin Barbarian Cheiftan &quot;cornered&quot; in a
cramped stairwell...  There were 3 &quot;effectives&quot; in the party and about 4
lower level followers.  The Hobgoblin was about 3 levels more advanced
than the main party members were... but lacked any allies or support at
all.

In the confined space of that stairwell, he just chewed the party and the
followers to bits... one at a time.  And by *MAKING* *SURE* that each was
dead before he moved on to the next one, he kept his job simple and
manageable.

Of course the hobgoblin died when his barbarian rage ran down and lost his
temporary hit points...  but that really was all he could ask for under
the circumstances, and he took an honor guard with him.

Once I understood it, it was a no-brainer... by finishing off each one of
his opponents irrevokably as they went down, he came out way ahead.  Once
the party realized what he was doing, they tried various things to prevent
it... like dragging the body away... and moving up to force the Hobgoblin
into a new engagement and keep him busy...  Which is exactly what the
hobgoblin wanted, close engagement in hand to hand combat.

No combatant dedicated to killing as many of their opponents as possible
should ever skip an opportunity to stab a fallen opponent that might not
be &quot;all dead&quot;.  It is a tactic sure to drive the good guys nuts and
motivate them to engage in behaviors that put them at a tactical
disadvantage that exposed them to risk in combat.  (Afterwards, of course,
the survivors should go through all the pockets and look for loose
change.)

