As a DM and a player I disagree with the 'finish them off' mentality.
For the most part Clerics are very very rare in the standard D&amp;D
setting.  Most bad guys would expect to be facing a group of warriors,
not the typical adventuring party, and would fight with that in mind.
It's a lot worse to waste an attack on someone who is out of the fight
than take out (or work on doing it) another opponent.

I play my enemies this way, and they are genuinely suprised when
someone whips out the healing, and adjust their fighting style at that
point. If they have any reason to know that one of the PCs is a healer
(survived an earlier fight, had done recon etc.) then they would act
in the 'finish them off' mode to begin with.  Of course this assumes
an intelligent opponent, and them having the goal of killing off the
party.  Beasts would most likely act differently depending on the
situation - hunting - they would try to get one of the party away for
a nice quiet meal, teritorial, attack the nearest and not persue, etc.

