If anything, 'making sure' ensures the PCs *do* do that sort of thing.
Without it it seems to normally be &quot;he's either dead, in which case
there's nothing to do right now, or dying, and either we can't do
anything or he'll stabilize&quot;.  Either way, there's no cause to risk
it to go in and save him *now*.

If they know he might either go from dying to dead (inconvenient) or
dead to dismembered (more inconvenient -- /raise dead/ doesn't fix that)
then there's a greater chance they'll 'act realistically' and try to
save him.  Or would have swapped him out before he got too hurt in the
first place.

D&amp;D doesn't model 'damaged and helpless' very well, unless the creature
is unconscious or dying.  This suits the genre and is in some ways
fairly realistic, but it's inconvenient for the 'wound them so they tie
up their allies helping them' mentality.  The closest we can get is what
we've been discussing, where they *have* to save their friend before
things get worse.

